{"author":"RebarBotNava","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context / Problem\n\nThe outbound differ is the last core module that *compares* in vendor shape.\n`outbound_differ.py:39-41` imports `_diff_fields`, `_extract_jira_field`, `_assignee_matches`,\nand `_LOCAL_TO_JIRA_TYPE` from `adapters.jira.outbound_fields`; the update path\n(`_compute_outbound_update_mutation`, call at `outbound_differ.py:732`) delegates to\n`_diff_fields` (`adapters/jira/outbound_fields.py:369-618`), which maps localâ†’Jira and then\nreads raw vendor snapshot keys (`fields.status.name`, `assignee.accountId`,\n`parent.key`, ADF `description`). These helpers have no ADR 0035 Â§(d)-legal home: on the\nBackend port they would force every backend to consume Jira snapshot dicts (exactly what plan\nreview blocked on the prior attempt, ticket 97f2 / Gerrit change 920); left in core they keep\nthe core vendor-shaped. Meanwhile the *inbound* differ already diffs canonically â€” it maps the\nvendor payload to local shape via the injected `InboundMapper` before comparing\n(`inbound_differ.py:159`). This asymmetry is the design flaw blocking epic bbf1 AC3.\n\n## Approach\n\nBring the outbound update path to parity with the inbound differ: **diff in canonical shape;\nvendor shapes cross core only as opaque payloads produced/consumed by port calls at the\nboundaries.**\n\n1. `run_differs.py` additionally passes `inbound_mapper=backend.inbound` to\n   `compute_outbound_mutations` (the backend object is already in scope there â€”\n   `run_differs.py:481-495` currently passes `outbound_mapper=backend.outbound`).\n2. `_compute_outbound_update_mutation` canonicalizes the snapshot entry with\n   `inbound_mapper.map_remote_to_local(jira_snapshot[jira_key])` (mirroring\n   `inbound_differ.py:159`) and compares the local ticket against the canonical remote using\n   new **neutral** field-comparison helpers in core (local vocabulary only).\n3. The changed-field set is computed in local field names; the vendor update payload is built\n   at the emission boundary by a NEW `OutboundMapper` method\n   `map_fields_to_remote(local_fields: dict[str, Any]) -> dict[str, Any]`: it takes exactly\n   the changed local-nameâ†’local-value subset and returns the vendor-shaped payload for those\n   fields only (the Jira implementation delegates to the same\n   `_map_local_to_jira_fields` machinery over the partial dict â€” a pure canonicalâ†’vendor\n   translation, Â§(d)-legal). The create path keeps using the whole-ticket\n   `map_local_to_remote` (`outbound_differ.py:632`). Rejected mechanisms: filtering a\n   full `map_local_to_remote(ticket)` result by the changed fields' vendor names â€” that\n   requires a localâ†’vendor field-name map in core (the exact knowledge the seam forbids) and\n   risks emitting mapper defaults for untouched fields; and a synthetic partial-ticket into\n   `map_local_to_remote` â€” its contract expects a full ticket and may default absent fields.\n   `OutboundMutation.fields` therefore stays vendor-shaped and the entire apply pipeline is\n   untouched (`batch_dispatch.py:107-110`, `dispatch_one.py:442-514` and the unpacked\n   `client.update_issue(issue_key, **fields)` at `dispatch_one.py:602`).\n4. Widen the Jira `InboundMapper` output (translation only, implemented in the vendor mapper\n   `inbound_fields.py:141-184` / delegate `adapters/jira/backend.py:43-47`) with three NEW,\n   exactly-named canonical keys, documented on the `InboundMapper` Protocol docstring in\n   `_backend.py` (the `map_remote_to_local` signature is unchanged â€” `dict[str, Any]` in/out;\n   today's scalar `assignee` string stays for existing consumers):\n   - `assignee_identity: dict` with fixed keys `{\"display\": str|None, \"email\": str|None,\n     \"account_id\": str|None}` â€” `account_id` is the backend's stable account identifier\n     (Jira: `accountId`; a GitHub backend would map its login/node id). Core replaces the\n     vendor shape-tolerant `_assignee_matches` (`adapters/jira/outbound_fields.py:237-261`)\n     with neutral membership matching (local value âˆˆ the non-None identity values),\n     preserving the both-empty match (`outbound_fields.py:251-252`).\n   - `remote_parent_id: str|None` (Jira: `fields.parent.key`) â€” a bare remote id string,\n     already port vocabulary per `RemoteRef`. Core compares the BindingStore-resolved\n     expected remote key against it, replacing `outbound_fields.py:531-558`.\n   - `reporter_identity: dict` (same fixed shape as `assignee_identity`) for the outbound\n     one-way reporter diff (`outbound_fields.py:346-366` and `:617`).\n4b. **The assignee resolver and the `_assignee_is_account_id` sentinel keep their exact\n   payload contract, re-homed Â§(d)-legally.** Today `_diff_fields` runs the assignee\n   resolver against the raw Jira assignee dict and injects\n   `changed[\"_assignee_is_account_id\"] = True` on the accountId fast-path\n   (`outbound_fields.py:471-530`, sentinel at `:508-513`), which `dispatch_one.py:488` pops\n   before submit. In the new flow, `OutboundMapper` gains\n   `resolve_assignee(local_value: str, remote_identity: dict | None) ->\n   tuple[Any, bool, bool]` â€” parameterized ONLY on the canonical `assignee_identity` shape\n   above (never on `jira_fields`), returning `(payload_value, authoritative,\n   is_account_id)`, the same 3-state contract as today's resolver: when\n   `authoritative=False` (no client / transient resolution error) the neutral differ falls\n   through to legacy string-match behavior exactly as `outbound_fields.py:488-491` does now.\n   The neutral differ decides *whether* assignee changed by membership matching, then calls\n   `resolve_assignee` at emission and sets the same `_assignee_is_account_id` sentinel key\n   in the payload from the returned flag â€” so the 264f accountId fast-path, the 9b94\n   unmappableâ†’unassign soft-fail, the non-authoritative fallback, and `dispatch_one.py:488`\n   are all byte-identical downstream.\n4c. **Labels canonicalize here too.** `_diff_labels` (`outbound_differ.py:755`) today reads\n   the raw `jira_fields.get(\"labels\")`. The Jira `map_remote_to_local` output gains\n   `labels: list[str]` (a pass-through translation of `fields.labels`), and `_diff_labels`\n   consumes the canonical list; identity-label exclusion semantics are unchanged (the\n   rebar-id back-pointer labels are already handled by the existing convention logic).\n5. Description parity: compare the port-sanitized local text\n   (`FieldSanitizer.sanitize_description`) against the mapper-decoded remote text, preserving\n   the ADF-fit + rstrip semantics of `outbound_fields.py:566-583`.\n6. Core policies stay in core, expressed on local field names: issuetype excluded on update\n   (today `outbound_fields.py:449-459`; the inbound differ already excludes `ticket_type`)\n   and inbound-directionality suppression (today `outbound_fields.py:467-470`).\n7. **The arbitration baseline is canonicalized at read time, storage unchanged.** The\n   per-binding baseline is *written* from raw remote snapshot entries and stored in vendor\n   field names/shapes (`binding_store.py:374` filters to `_BASELINE_FIELDS`,\n   `binding_store.py:71`; writers pass `prev_snapshot[jira_key]` / `curr_snapshot[jira_key]`\n   at `binding_store.py:390`, `reconcile.py:520`, `apply_inbound_records.py:212`). Per the\n   canonical-comparison principle it is a stored remote payload: it stays vendor-shaped at\n   rest (opaque; NO data migration, writers untouched), and the outbound differ's\n   suppression/conflict path applies `inbound_mapper.map_remote_to_local` to the baseline\n   entry at the same ingestion boundary as the snapshot. The vendor suppression helpers\n   (`_local_matches_prev`/`_jira_matches_prev`, which today call `_extract_jira_field` on\n   vendor-nested values) are replaced by neutral canonical-name equivalents, and the\n   outboundâ†”inbound field-name reconciliation (`summary` vs `title`) disappears because\n   baseline, snapshot, and local ticket all compare in local names after mapping. The Jira\n   `map_remote_to_local` must therefore tolerate a partial fields dict (the\n   `_BASELINE_FIELDS` subset) â€” mapping only the keys present. Other baseline consumers\n   (e.g. `binding_walk.py:192`) are out of scope and keep reading the stored vendor shape.\n8. `_diff_fields` / `_extract_jira_field` / `_assignee_matches` / `_LOCAL_TO_JIRA_TYPE` become\n   adapter-internal; the `outbound_differ.py:39-43` imports are deleted and the test-suite\n   re-exports migrate to `adapters.jira.outbound_fields`. The bound-but-absent direct-GET path\n   is unchanged: the `absent_alive_fields` return (`outbound_differ.py:432-443`, populated at\n   `:730`) remains a raw vendor dict passed through core opaquely (core never reads into it).\n9. Amend ADR 0035 Â§(d) (`docs/adr/0035-reconciler-vendor-adapter-seam.md`) to pin the\n   principle: *core compares only canonical shapes; the outbound differ canonicalizes the\n   snapshot via `InboundMapper` and emits vendor payloads only via `OutboundMapper`.* The\n   amendment states its delivery precisely â€” this story canonicalizes the FIELD, LABEL, and\n   BASELINE comparison paths; the LINK comparison path (`_diff_link_mutations` at\n   `outbound_differ.py:767` via `outbound_links._existing_jira_links`) is canonicalized by\n   the sibling story `eefd-49b1-995f-488d` under the same epic, and the ADR text marks it as\n   delivered there â€” so the principle is not overclaimed while the epic is in flight.\n\nRejected alternatives: (a) putting the vendor-shaped comparison helpers on the port â€” already\nBLOCKED by plan review as an Â§(d) violation (port methods parameterized on `jira_fields`\ndicts); (b) re-shaping `OutboundMutation.fields` to canonical and mapping in the applier â€”\ntouches the whole dispatch pipeline (`batch_dispatch`/`dispatch_one`/`apply_handlers`/\n`apply_outbound`) for no additional neutrality, since emission-boundary mapping in the differ\nalready keeps vendor shape out of core logic.\n\nBehavior risk, named: the old differ compares in Jira value-space (mapped local vs raw\nremote), the new one in local value-space (local vs inbound-mapped remote). Where the\nlocalâ†”Jira status/priority value maps are not inverse-consistent, or the remote status does\nnot map (the inbound mapper emits `status` only when mapped, `inbound_fields.py:167-176` â€”\nthe neutral helper must treat canonical-status-absent + local-status-present as a diff, since\nlocal wins), decisions could drift. The characterization suite below pins decision-for-\ndecision equivalence before the old helpers are demoted.\n\n## Scope\n\n- src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/outbound_differ.py (canonical comparison; neutral helpers; emission-boundary mapping)\n- src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/run_differs.py (pass inbound_mapper=backend.inbound)\n- src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/_backend.py (InboundMapper contract note: canonical output incl. identity aliases + parent remote id)\n- src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/inbound_fields.py (Jira mapper: aliases, parent remote id, reporter aliases)\n- src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/adapters/jira/backend.py (delegate surface)\n- src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/adapters/jira/outbound_fields.py (helpers become adapter-internal)\n- docs/adr/0035-reconciler-vendor-adapter-seam.md (Â§(d) canonical-comparison amendment)\n- tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_backend_neutrality.py (AST gate extended to outbound_differ.py)\n- tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/ (new characterization suite; migrated re-export tests)\n\n## Testing\n\n- Happy path: a bound ticket with one changed field emits an update whose vendor payload\n  equals today's (port-mapped); an unchanged ticket emits nothing.\n- Characterization (old-vs-new decision equivalence): identical emit/no-emit decisions and\n  payloads across the full localâ†”Jira status and priority value maps; assignee shapes\n  (accountId / emailAddress / displayName / both-empty), including the accountId fast-path\n  emitting the `_assignee_is_account_id` sentinel and the unmappableâ†’unassign soft-fail\n  (resolver re-homed as `OutboundMapper.resolve_assignee`); absent parent and parent change;\n  ADF description fit+rstrip; inbound-directionality suppression driven by a vendor-shaped\n  stored baseline (suppression still fires after canonicalization â€” the regression the old\n  shape mismatch would silently cause is unconditional local-wins); conflict detection via\n  the canonicalized baseline; a partial `_BASELINE_FIELDS` subset dict through\n  `map_remote_to_local`; label add/remove decisions via the canonical `labels` list\n  (identity labels still excluded); the non-authoritative assignee-resolver fallback to\n  legacy string-match; unmapped remote status.\n- Runtime proof: the update path builds its payload exclusively via the injected\n  `OutboundMapper` (mirroring `test_outbound_differ_uses_injected_mapper`,\n  `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_backend_neutrality.py:189-213`).\n- Edge: snapshot entry missing/deleted sentinels (`_DELETED`/`_TRANSPORT_ERROR`) behave as\n  today; `absent_alive_fields` passthrough unchanged.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `outbound_differ.py` contains NO `adapters.jira` import (module-level or\n      function-nested) â€” verified by the extended AST case in\n      `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_backend_neutrality.py`.\n- [ ] The update path canonicalizes the snapshot via the injected `InboundMapper` before any\n      comparison (runtime proof: a spy `InboundMapper` on a `FakeBackend` observes the\n      snapshot entry for every bound update candidate), and `outbound_differ.py` contains\n      none of the vendor payload key literals `\"accountId\"`, `\"emailAddress\"`,\n      `\"displayName\"`, `\"issuetype\"`, `\"issuelinks\"`, `\"inwardIssue\"`, `\"outwardIssue\"` â€”\n      verified by a deterministic source-text denylist case added to\n      `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_backend_neutrality.py` (the vendor-key reads live\n      only under `adapters/jira/`).\n- [ ] The characterization suite proving old-vs-new decision equivalence (cases enumerated in\n      Testing) is green â€” verified by `pytest` on the new test file.\n- [ ] ADR 0035 Â§(d) records the canonical-comparison principle â€” verified by the amended ADR\n      text in the change.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` green; whole test tree collects with 0 errors.\n\n## Plan-review remediation (drift re-review, G1G2 findings)\n\nThree executor-ambiguities are pinned here:\n\n1. **Partial-baseline `map_remote_to_local` â€” exact absent-key semantics (Step 7).** The Jira\n   `_map_jira_to_local_fields` today reads each field as `_extract_jira_field_value(f, k) or\n   <default>`, which DEFAULTS absent keys. It is made partial-tolerant by guarding each field's\n   emission on vendor-key PRESENCE (`if k in jira_fields`), NOT on truthiness:\n   - A vendor key PRESENT (even with a null/empty value) maps exactly as today (null â†’ today's\n     default/empty), so a FULL remote snapshot is byte-for-byte unchanged.\n   - A vendor key ABSENT from the input dict yields NO corresponding canonical key in the output\n     (it is NOT defaulted). So a partial `_BASELINE_FIELDS` subset maps only the keys actually\n     recorded.\n   - Absent canonical key at comparison time == \"no baseline ancestor for that field\" == the\n     existing per-field local-wins signal (ADR 0026 Â§2): the arbitration/suppression path skips\n     a field with no baseline entry, exactly as a `None` whole-baseline does today. This\n     preserves decision-for-decision equivalence and keeps stored remote payloads opaque at rest\n     (canonicalize at read only).\n   The three new canonical alias keys follow the same presence rule: `assignee_identity` emitted\n   only when `\"assignee\"` is present, `remote_parent_id` only when `\"parent\"` is present,\n   `reporter_identity` only when `\"reporter\"` is present.\n\n2. **Naming fix (Â§9 / link path).** The outbound link comparison function is `_diff_links`\n   (imported into `outbound_differ.py` from `outbound_links.py`), NOT `_diff_link_mutations`\n   (which does not exist). Links are OUT of 625b's code scope â€” sibling story eefd owns the link\n   path; 625b only notes in the ADR that LINK is delivered under eefd. 625b makes no change to\n   `_diff_links`.\n\n3. **`map_remote_to_local` signature is unchanged** (`dict[str, Any] -> dict[str, Any]`); the\n   partial-tolerance is purely internal (per-field presence guard). Existing full-snapshot\n   consumers (`inbound_differ.py:159`) are unaffected because a full snapshot has every key\n   present.\n\n**Added acceptance criteria:**\n- [ ] `map_remote_to_local` maps a partial `_BASELINE_FIELDS` subset by emitting ONLY the\n      canonical keys whose vendor source key is PRESENT (absent vendor key -> absent canonical\n      key, never a default), while a FULL snapshot maps byte-identically to today â€” verified by\n      a partial-input test and a full-input equivalence test.\n- [ ] A field absent from the canonicalized baseline is treated as \"no ancestor\" (per-field\n      local-wins), matching today's whole-`None`-baseline arbitration â€” verified by a\n      characterization case in the equivalence suite."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784832306016567001,"uuid":"3c9ed1ff-1e32-4656-8fbe-51483a747abb"}